                            <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Domain-driven+design%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">
                              JSTOR
                            </a>
                          </span>
                        </small>
                      </span>
                      <small class="date-container">
                        <i>
                          (
                          <span class="date">
                            July 2019
                          </span>
                          )
                        </i>
                      </small>
                      <small class="hide-when-compact">
                        <i>
                           (
                          <a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">
                            Learn how and when to remove this template message
                          </a>
                          )
                        </i>
                      </small>
                    </div>
                  </td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
            <p>
              <b>
                Domain-driven design
              </b>
               (
              <b>
                DDD
              </b>
              ) is an approach to 
              <a href="/wiki/Software_development" title="Software development">
                software development
              </a>
               for complex needs by connecting the 
              <a href="/wiki/Implementation" title="Implementation">
                implementation
              </a>
               to an evolving model.
              <sup id="cite_ref-definition_1-0" class="reference">
                <a href="#cite_note-definition-1">
                  [1]
                </a>
              </sup>
            </p>
            <p>
              Domain-driven design is predicated on the following goals:

            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                placing the project's primary focus on the core 
                <a href="/wiki/Domain_(software_engineering)" title="Domain (software engineering)">
                  domain
                </a>
                 and domain logic;
              </li>
              <li>
                basing complex designs on a model of the domain;
              </li>
              <li>
                initiating a creative collaboration between technical and 
                <a href="/wiki/Domain_expert" class="mw-redirect" title="Domain expert">
                  domain experts
                </a>
                 to iteratively refine a conceptual model that addresses particular domain problems.
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              The term was coined by 
              <a href="/w/index.php?title=Eric_Evans_(technologist)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Eric Evans (technologist) (page does not exist)">
                Eric Evans
              </a>
               in his book of the same title.
              <sup id="cite_ref-book.evans_2-0" class="reference">
                <a href="#cite_note-book.evans-2">
                  [2]
                </a>
              </sup>
            </p>
            <div id="toc" class="toc">
              <input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" value="on"/>
